ighbors shared its fundamental ideological principles, such as unity under a single monarch--hence, even the empire's strongest domestic and foreign foes adopted the system of imperial rule. Yet details of this rule were constantly negotiated and adjusted. Pines shows how deep tensions between political actors including the emperor, the literati, local elites, and rebellious commoners actually enabled the empire's basic institutional framework to remain critically vital and adaptable to ever-changing sociopolitical circumstances. As contemporary China moves toward a new period of prosperity and power in the twenty-first century, Pines argues that the legacy of the empire may become an increasingly important force in shaping the nation's future trajectory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aIdeologyzChinaxHistory. 0aImperialismxHistory. 0aImperialismzChinaxHistory. 0aPolitical culturezChinaxHistory. 0aPolitical sciencezChinaxPhilosophyxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh  aAll-under-Heaven.  aChinese emperor.  aChinese emperorship.  aChinese empire.  aChinese history.  aChinese imperial experience.  aChinese intellectuals.  aChinese political culture.  aChinese political system.  aRepublic of China.  aadministrative power.  abalances.  abureaucracy.  achecks.  acommoners.  acontemporary China.  acultural foundations.  adepersonalization.  aeducated elite.  aflawed morality.  afragmentation.  agovernment apparatus.  ahistorical changes.  aimperial history.  aimperial ideology.  aimperial political culture.  aimperial political structure.  aimperial unification.  ainstitution.  aintellectual elitism.  alarge-scale uprisings.  alocal elites.  amodern China.  amodernity.  amonarch.  amonarchism.  amonarchy.  aomnipotent.  a